Project: Unsupervised Learning¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on Unsupervised Learning. We will be using the Credit Card Customer Data for this project.

Context:¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective:¶

Identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

About the data:¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

  • Sl_no - Customer Serial Number
  • Customer Key - Customer identification
  • Avg_Credit_Limit - Average credit limit (currency is not specified, you can make an assumption around this)
  • Total_Credit_Cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total_visits_bank - Total bank visits
  • Total_visits_online - Total online visits
  • Total_calls_made - Total calls made

K-Means Clustering¶

Let us now fit k-means algorithm on our scaled data and find out the optimum number of clusters to use.

We will do this in 3 steps:

  1. Initialize a dictionary to store the SSE for each k
  2. Run for a range of Ks and store SSE for each run
  3. Plot the SSE vs K and find the elbow

# Let's assign points to 3 different groups
def grouping(x):
    first_component = x['Component 1']
    second_component = x['Component 2']
    if (first_component<-30) and (second_component <0): 
        return 'group_2'
    if (second_component <10 ) and (first_component >-20):
        return 'group_1'
    else: 
        return 'group_0'

Elbow Method to estimate number of clusters¶

In [28]:
# step 1
sse = {} 

# step 2 - iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Use inertia attribute from the clustering object and 
# store the inertia value for that k 
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, max_iter=1000, random_state=1).fit(data_scaled)
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_

# step 3
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("SSE")
plt.show()
  • Looking at the plot, we can say that elbow point is achieved for k=3.
  • We will fit the k-means again with k=3 to get the labels
  • Our tSNE analysis above corroborates this point about 3 clusters

SILHOUETTE ANALYSIS¶

In [29]:
#Empty dictionary to store the Silhouette score for each value of k
sc = {} 

# iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Store the Silhouette score for that k 
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(data_scaled)
    labels = kmeans.predict(data_scaled)
    sc[k] = silhouette_score(data_scaled, labels)

#Elbow plot
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.show()

Observations¶

  • As seen in the chart above, the silhouette score is highest at the point k = 3
  • Based on the above evidence we start with the number of clusters = 3

Observations: Cluster Profile¶

  • The first group (group_0) has 289 (44.9%) data points and comprises of people with low credit score (group average is ~12k), low number of cards (group average is ~2.4), average ~1 visit to the bank, average ~3.5 online visits and average ~6.9 calls made (highest amoung all groups)
  • The second group (group_1) has 222 data points (~34.4%) and comprises of people with the highest (average ~85k) credit limit, highest number of lines of credit (average ~7) credit cards, ~1.7 visits to the bank on average, ~4.6 online visits on average and ~2 average calls made
  • The third group (group_2) is the smallest cluster with 133 data points (appx 20.7%) comprises of people with credit limit of 28k on average, ~5 lines of credit on average, ~3.8 bank visits on average and average appx 1.85 calla made and online visits ~1 on average

Observations: Comparison¶

  • Although cluster one (group_0) size goes down by 13.2% in the case of KMedoids, the cluster characteristics stay the same
  • The second cluster (group 1) is the same size but its profile changes completely. It now includes the customers with high credit limit (85k) and maximum lines of credit (up 1.5 units vs KMeans to 7 credit cards on average), even lower visits to the bank (down 1.8 units), high online visits (4.6) and low calls made (~2)
  • The third cluster (group_2) now has a larger size (up 13% vs KMeans) and comprises of the middle of the spectrum customers with average 28k credit limit where most of them have a credit limit of 20k, average number of lines of credit is 5.4 vs 8.8 and most customers have 5 credit cards (down 4 units), the bank visits are up to average of 3.8 vs .6 and most customers visit 9 times, online visit down to ~1 vs ~11 and total calls ~1.8 which was slightly higher than 1.1 in KMeans clusters
  • The premium customer profile in case of KMedoids is slightly different with mean credit limit 85k vs 140k in case of KMeans, most of these customers hav a credit limit of 145k in the KMeans analysis but is 68K per KMedoids
  • group_1 now shows an equal tendency to use online vs visit vs calls at most customers using these channels 2 times
  • group_2 shows highest tendency to visit the bank

Conclusion:¶

Although the choice of algorithm would be based on many other criteria, the KMeans method give more distinct clusters and hence should be the preferred algorithm¶
